Navigating SXSW Conference

Theme and Size

·     Theme: Looking to the Future

·     24 Tracks

·     1,500+ Sessions

·     Size: (2023 statistics for reference)

·     76,000+ Attendees

·     3,000 Conference Speakers

·     126 Countries Represented

SXSW Badge Pickup

·     When:  March 6, 8:00am - 6:00pm; March 7-8, 8:00am - 11:00pm (CDT)

·     Where:  Austin Convention Center, 500 E Cesar Chavez St, Austin, TX 78701

·     Pickup:  Exhibit Hall 1 (on the Trinity St side of the building)

·     How:  A government-issued photo ID is required to collect and maintain your credentials.

·     SXSW Badge Pickup

·     Recommendation: Pick up your badge when you arrive!

Austin Downtown Maps & Safety

Maps

·     Austin City Map, Visitor Guide Map, Lady Bird Lake Trail Map and Zilker Park Map

·     Downtown Maps  

Safety

·     Downtown is well-lit and frequented by locals and tourists, especially during events.

·     Still, it's always crucial to stay alert and take precautions.

·     You are encouraged to walk in pairs.

·     There is a downtown presence of individuals experiencing homelessness.

·     It is advisable to use ride-sharing services for venturing far out or for late-night travel.

SXSW Conference Schedule, Tracks & Sessions

Schedule

·     Review and search the schedule by date, event type, presenter, and track.

·     Link

Tracks and Sessions Overview

·     24 Conference Tracks with 1,500 sessions.

·     Search sessions by track, key word, presenter, etc.

·     Next to each track is the number of sessions under that track. Tracks with a higher number of sessions is mainly due to the number of “mentor sessions” offered.

·     Sessions – Get Started  

Helpful Hints

·     When considering a session, confirm on the session page that your Interactive or Platinum badge gets you entry into the session. Which badges receive entry is provided on each session’s landing page.

·     When you search the full schedule by track, the generated list will include all sessions, even those designated under another track.

·     Another option is to access the schedule and run your own search by using the search field. For example, “Native” is not listed as a track, session or tag. However, if you complete an independent search using the word “Native”, a list is generated with all sessions that include the word “Native”.

Summary of Tracks & Corresponding Sessions

2050 Track

·     Showcases long-range, big-picture thinking across interplanetary exploration and quantum to new science discoveries and neurotech breakthroughs.

·     48 Sessions that include topics on emotions and AI, neurotech, human longevity, quantum computing, quantum leap, climate, next pandemic, NASA, spatial computing, robot apocalypse and more.

Austin Ecosystem Leaders

Army Applications Laboratory (AAL)

   Dr. Casey Perley, Executive Director

·     Uses its Alignment Blueprint to coordinate projects, resources, and communities against critical Army problems.

·     Tests and refines business models that can scale across the Army.

·     Helps challenge the Army's conventional approach to capability development and provide new ways for industry and the military to work together.

Army Futures Command

·     Leadership

·     AFC transforms the Army to ensure war-winning future readiness.

·     Headquartered in Austin, AFC has more than 17,000 personnel worldwide.

·     Newest of the Army’s four major commands.

·     Established in 2018 to ensure the Army and its Soldiers remain at the forefront of technological innovation and warfighting ability.

·     Focuses on prioritizing people, designing Army 2040 and delivering Army 2030.

·     Advances the Army's modernization priorities: long range precision fires, next generation combat vehicle, future vertical lift, air and missile defense, network and Soldier lethality.

 

Austin Technology Council

   Thom Singer, CEO

·     Board of Directors

·     Provides knowledge and access in the areas of talent, business mentoring and networking.

·     Advocates for a robust, supportive environment for tech companies through public policy, education and thought leadership.

·     Provides access to community, collaboration, and conversations with those who can share best practices.

 

 

 

 

 

 

 

 

 

Austin Technology Incubator

   Rebecca (Becky) Taylor, Interim Executive Director

·     Leadership Team & Executives in Residence

·     Founded in 1989, by Dr. George Kozmetsky, first led by Laura Kilcrease.

·     Deep technology incubator of The University of Texas at Austin working with university and community entrepreneurs to commercialize its breakthrough innovations.

·     Home to incubators focused on Circular Economy, Energy, Food + AgTech, Healthcare/Biotech, Mobility, and Water.


Austin Venture Association

   David Valentino, Managing Director

·     Advisory Board

·     Organization focused on supporting a community of VCs and organizations servicing early stage and emerging startups in Austin. The goal is to support the Austin venture community in growing and building stronger businesses in Austin.

Capital Factory

   Joshua Baer, Founder & CEO

·     Executives

·     List of Mentors (175+ searchable by industry, title and listed alphabetically by first name)

·     Place where the tech community comes together to learn and connect. Offers membership opportunities with coworking and joining the Austin tech ecosystem. 900+ annual tech and community events. Home to hundreds of startups in software, hardware and innovation. Network of mentors, investors and startup resources. Provides its startups with tools needed to help their companies grow and thrive.

 

DivInc

   Preston James, Co-Founder & CEO

·     Board of Directors

·     Focused on making the startup community diverse, equitable, and inclusive for people of color, women, and all underrepresented entrepreneurs. Helps reduce the racial and gender wealth divide and drive innovation. Four accelerators: Clean Energy Accelerator, Women in Tech, Sports Tech Accelerator and Social Impact Tech Accelerator.

 

F.I.E.S.T.A.

   Cherie Werner, Founder & CEO

·     FIESTA (Founders, Entrepreneurs & Austin Newcomers) supports startup founders and those new to Austin. Connects founders and entrepreneurs. 6,400 members.

 

Texas Venture Alliance

   Christa “CS” Freeland, Cofounder

·     Statewide VC network and ecosystem of startup support in Texas that amplifies, advocates and connects. Its mission is to amplify ecosystem of startup support, advocate for startups and investors at the Texas State Capitol. Amplifies a Texas-sized ecosystem of startup support.

Angel Networks

Central Texas Angel Network

·     CTAN is one of the most active investing groups in U.S. Since 2006, it has invested $125MM in 208 companies. Focused on innovative, scalable, and competitive startups.

 

SWAN Impact Network

·     Mission to bring as much capital as possible to support startups working to make the world a better place. Focused on Health and Wellness, Environment, Empowerment, Education and Nonprofits.


Austin Accelerators & Incubators

Austin Community College Fashion Incubator

·     High-tech facility that supports students and local fashion industry.

·     Partners with the City of Austin Economic Development Dept to provide an industry experience to develop a local workforce in the fashion industry.

·     Partners with Gerber Technology on a unique digital solutions package that reduces product development and production costs for designers.

Austin Technology Incubator

·     Deep technology incubator of UT Austin working with university and community entrepreneurs to commercialize its breakthrough innovations.

·     Home to a few specialized incubators: Circular Economy, Energy, Food + AgTech, Healthcare/Biotech, Mobility, and Water.

Bunker Labs

·     Focused on active-duty military, veterans and their spouses.

·     Provides community, programs, and courses to help military veterans and military spouses start and grow successful businesses and startups.

 

 

 

 

Capital Factory Accelerator Program

·     Serves tech startups in all stages — from first-time entrepreneurs to late-stage tech companies through access to workspace, mentors and programming and events.

·     Texas-based program offers valuable expertise and resources for Seed tech companies, along with access to a network of investors and Texas venture capital firms.

DivInc Accelerator Programs

·     DivInc focuses on diverse founders with a mission to generate social and economic equity through entrepreneurship.

·     Clean Energy Accelerator ensures inclusive clean energy transition.

·     Women in Tech supports and amplifies women-led tech startups.

·     Sports Tech Accelerator supports startups using tech to enhance health and wellness, fan experience, the future of media, sports betting, esports and gaming.

·     Social Impact Tech Accelerator that helps social enterprise startups to develop global solutions or services that increase access and equity across any industry sector in our society.

 

Founder Institute

·     Turns ideas into fundable startups and startups into global businesses.

·     Austin Spring 2024 Mentors

 

International Accelerator

·     Helps foreign-born founders, creators and entrepreneurs launch in the U.S.

·     From free housing and office space to relocation and legal support, it provides a network of investors, experts and mentors to help them navigate the challenges of launching their company in the U.S.

John Brumley Texas Venture Labs

·     Part of UT Austin. It accelerates startups, takes their innovations to market and transforms graduate students into entrepreneurs and business growers.

·     Provides venues for investors to engage with UT research and startups.

·     Matches early-stage Texas-based startups with cross-functional student teams from across UT’s graduate schools to help solve business problems.

Mass Challenge Accelerators

·     Its mission is to equip entrepreneurs to disrupt status quo and create meaningful change.

·     Early-stage, founder-focused and industry agnostic.

Oracle Startup Cloud Accelerator

·     Open to early-stage technology and technology-enabled startups.

·     Residential and non-residential program. Residential accelerator has locations in Austin, Bangalore, Bristol, Delhi, Mumbai, Paris, São Paulo, Singapore and Tel Aviv.

Oracle NetSuite Accelerator

·     Encourages diversity in entrepreneurship. The goal is to help founders and leaders from diverse communities build successful, sustainable businesses.

·     Supports founders and leaders from diverse communities: Black, women, Veteran, LGBTQ, Asian, disabled and Latinx.

 

 

 

Plug and Play Texas - Cedar Park

·     Works with regional partners in Cedar Park to address needs of local businesses and communities.

·     Focus areas: Advanced Manufacturing, Enterprise, AI and Healthtech.

·     Since 2006, it has accelerated startups, matched them with corporate clients, and invested in them.

SKU

·     Ecosystem that creates lasting change in consumer-packaged goods (CPG). Provides founders with resources needed to accelerate the growth of their brands.

·     Driven by a community of the nation's top CPG leaders, founders and industry experts.

Sputnik ATX VC

·     Early-stage VC fund that combines capital with training and experience so startup founders can reach their full potential.

·     Portfolio of startups and founders that are solving real problems and creating consumer surplus for their customers.

 

STAR Park

·     Division of Research at Texas State University. The Science, Technology, and Advanced Research Park.

·     58-acre site that hosts STAR One, the first technology incubator dedicated to research and commercialization efforts.

·     Incubator program was designed to foster the collaborative development of new commercial ventures in applied research. For start-up and early-stage businesses it provides wet labs, clean space, conference rooms and office space.

Tech Ranch Austin

·     Helps innovators, startups, and scaleups get access to markets to drive global impact through enabling relationships, resources, and practices.

·     Entrepreneurs gain operational and tactical insight and community support to spur innovation that addresses local and global challenges.

Small, Downtown Grocery Store

Royal Blue Grocery

·     607 Congress Ave, Austin, TX 78701

·     Compact urban market that opened its doors in 2006. It offers a little bit of everything, from Proud Mary coffee and freshly prepared grab-and-go offerings to conventional grocery and convenience items, with always tons of locally sourced products from unique brands. Walking distance.


Coffee Spots

Better Half Coffee & Cocktails

·     406 Walsh St, Austin, TX 78703

·     An award-winning all-day cafe located just west of downtown Austin. Early, late, brunch, espresso, cocktails and beer. Lots of outdoor seating to grab a bite and take a meeting. Quick Uber/Lyft from downtown.

 

Codependent Cocktails + Coffee

·     301 West Ave, Suite #110 Austin, TX 78701

·     Coffee house by day and cocktail bar by night. Great drinks and bites. Grab a table to work and/or take a meeting. Walking distance.

 

Halcyon

·     218 W 4th Street, Austin, TX 78701

·     A Warehouse District all-day cafe. Coffee shop by day and a bar that’s open until 2:00am with cocktails, wine and beer. Walking distance.

Houndstooth Coffee

·     401 Congress Ave, Austin, TX 78701

·     Rated as one of the best coffee houses in Austin. Hidden in the base of the Frost Bank Tower. During peak hours it gets busy. Walking distance.

 

Merit Coffee Co.

·     222 West Ave #120, Austin, TX 78701

·     Located in the Seaholm district is a great place to meet up with people or get some work done Downtown. They roast their own beans—and there’s some outdoor seating, Tacodeli tacos, and pastries. Quick Uber/Lyft from downtown.

Tacos

Tacodeli

·     301 Congress, Austin, TX 78701

·     Owner first opened his restaurant in Mexico City, where he grew up, and then he opened in Austin. Locally owned and sourced, and opened in 1999. A bit of a walk from downtown but easy. * Most coffee shops sell Tacodeli breakfast tacos. Walking distance.

 

Torchy’s Tacos

·     110 San Antonio St Unit #120, Austin, TX 78701

·     A local rivalry of the best taco in Austin. Recipes made from scratch. Locally owned and opened in 2006. Located downtown. Walking distance.

BBQ

Franklin Barbeque

·     901 E 11th, Austin, TX 78702

·     It is the winner of every BBQ award there is. The line forms many hours before it opens. It closes when they run out of BBQ, which is typically around 2pm. Family-owned and opened in 2009. Quick Uber/Lyft from downtown

 

Loro

·     2115 South Lamar Blvd. Austin, TX 78704

·     An Asian smokehouse and bar brought to you by the award-winning chefs behind Uchi and Franklin Barbecue. Together, they merged their love of Asian cuisine and Texas barbecue to offer innovative dishes you won’t find anywhere else. Locally owned and opened in 2018. Uber/Lyft from downtown.

Stiles Switch BBQ

·     6610 North Lamar Blvd, Austin, TX 78752

·     BBQ and Frito pie. Locally owned and opened in 2011. Uber/Lyft from downtown.

 

 

 

Terry Black’s BBQ

·     1003 Barton Springs Road, Austin, TX 78704

·     The line will be long, and they will run out of items throughout the day. Family-owned and 4th generation pitmaster. Opened in 2014. Use the Hike & Bike Trail to shorten your walk or it’s a quick Uber/Lyft.

Mexican / Tex-Mex

Cisco’s Restaurant, Bakery & Bar

·     1511 E 6th St, Austin, TX 78702

·     Migas, huevos rancheros, fajitas, tacos, margaritas, beer and more. You walk through the kitchen to take a seat, and the walls are lined with a snapshot of Texas’ political history. Family-owned and opened in 1948. Quick Uber/Lyft from downtown.

 

El Patio

·     2938 Guadalupe Street, Austin, TX 78705

·     The Mexican food menu has barely changed since it opened. Family-owned by five generations and opened in 1954. Uber/Lyft from downtown.

Fonda San Miguel

·     2330 W North Loop, Austin, TX 78756

·     Serves interior Mexican food. 2 best-selling cookbooks and supposedly Elon Musk’s favorite Mexican food restaurant. Nicer, more expensive restaurant. Locally owned and opened in 1975. Uber/Lyft from downtown.

Guero’s

·     1412 S Congress Ave, Austin, TX 78701

·     Interior Mexican and Tex-Mex food. 2nd generation, family-owned and opened in 1986. Food and live music. The restaurant is likely to have a SXSW private party. Long walk down Sown Congress or quick Uber/Lyft from downtown.

Matt’s El Rancho

·     2613 S Lamar Blvd, Austin, TX 78704

·     First Tex-Mex food restaurant in Austin. President Lyndon Johnson had a soft spot for Matt's famous chile rellenos and often sent a jet from Washington D.C. to pick up his El Rancho favorites. Family-owned and opened in 1952. Uber/Lyft from downtown.

Mr. Natural

·     1901 East Cesar Chavez, Austin, TX 78702

·     Healthy, homestyle Mexican food. Owners firmly believe that good nutrition starts at the dining table. Everything is made in house, from their grandmother's refried beans to the bread on the sandwiches. Family-owned and opened in 1988. Quick Uber/Lyft from downtown.

Pizza, Burgers and Chili

Home Slice Pizza

·     1415 S Congress, Austin, TX 78704

·     Has a passion for food and a vision for an Austin institution based on the original, unfailing goodness of authentic NY-style pizza. Locally owned and opened in 2005. Long walk down Sown Congress or quick Uber/Lyft from downtown.

 

Sandy’s Old Fashioned Hamburgers

·     603 Barton Springs Road, Austin, TX 78704

·     Old-school burger stand with no-frills burgers and frozen custard. Grab and go. Homegrown and opened in 1945. Use the Hike & Bike Trail to shorten your walk or it’s a quick Uber/Lyft from downtown. (Located a couple of blocks from Terry Black's BBQ.)

Texas Chili Parlor

·     1409 Lavaca Street, Austin, TX 78701

·     Order chili by the level of heat you can handle. Chili was named the official food of Texas one year after it opened. Early history of rabble-rousers and soon to be Texas politicians. Hand-painted rules on the wall of the dive:” No checks… no foofoo drinks, no talking to imaginary people.” Very small and gets busy quickly. Locally owned and opened in 1976. Quick Uber/Lyft from downtown.

“Old Austin” Dives and Honky Tonks

Donn’s Depot

·     1600 W 5th St, Austin, TX 78703

·     An old saloon located in an old train depot. A bar and no kitchen. 21 and up. Locally owned and opened in 1978. Quick Uber/Lyft from downtown.

Scholz Garten

·     1607 San Jacinto Blvd, Austin, TX 78701

·     Hot spot for politicians (liberals and conservatives), UT football fans and music lovers. The Texas Legislature passed House Resolution #68, which recognized it as “a gathering place for Texans…” Homegrown and opened in 1866. Oldest restaurant in America. Indoor and outdoor seating. Quick Uber/Lyft from downtown.

 

Broken Spoke

·     3201 S Lamar Blvd, Austin, TX 78704

·     Legendary honky tonk, bar and restaurant. Chicken fried steak is on the menu, and Lone Star beer is the only beer on tap. “Last of the true dance halls”. Willie Nelson, Dolly Parton, Garth Brooks, Dwight Yoakam and Joe Ely have played, and the list goes on and on. Favorite spot for celebrities and more recent bands. Walls are lined with star studded photos. Family-owned and opened in 1964. Uber/Lyft from downtown. * Big names often drop by with no advance notice and take the stage during SXSW.

Popular Attractions

Hike & Bike Trail (10 miles of trail to walk and run)

·     It is a low-grade trail, most of which is wide enough to accommodate both cyclists and pedestrian traffic. Because the trail winds through downtown, there are access points and parking all along the route, making it easy to choose your distance, detours, and side trips, all in view of the Austin skyline. Walking distance.

·     Trail map.

 

 

 

 

Stevie Ray Vaughan Statue

·     In 1993, the City of Austin erected the Stevie Ray Vaughan Memorial Statue at Auditorium Shores on Lady Bird Lake, the site of several of Vaughan’s concerts.

·     Located on the Hike & Bike Trail. Walking distance.

Barton Springs Pool

·     Within Zilker Park's 358 acres lies Barton Springs Pool. The pool is three acres in size and is fed from underground springs with an average temperature of 68-70 degrees. It is listed as a federally protected habitat.

·     Buy an entry ticket at a kiosk when you arrive. Quick Uber/Lyft from downtown.

South Congress

·     An avenue full of restaurants, shopping, bars, and events. Not to mention a constant supply of live music. Only the best businesses survive here, so you can be sure it's worth your time.

·     Austin just wouldn't be Austin without South Congress, and it's the vein that leads straight to the heart of Texas.

·     A long walk or quick Uber/Lyft from downtown.

The Texas Capitol

·     The Texas Capitol is surrounded by approximately 22 acres.

·     In 1993, the completion of the Capitol Extension created an entirely new setting for the north side of the Capitol.

·     The 1995-96 restoration of the historic South Grounds returned the park-like setting to its 1888-1915 appearance.

·     Located at the north end of South Congress. Walking distance.
